import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import norm
from ipywidgets import interact, Dropdown



def qq_plot(df):
    """
    Generate a Q-Q plot with 95% confidence interval for a DataFrame with multiple columns.
    Args:
        df (pandas.DataFrame): Input DataFrame with numerical columns.
    """

    # Dropdown menu options
    column_options = Dropdown(options=df.columns.tolist(), description='Select Column:')

    @interact(column=column_options)
    def plot_qq(column):
        # Get the column data
        y = df[column]

        # Calculate the necessary values using the DS_Q_Q_Plot function
        n = len(y)
        y_os = np.sort(y)
        mu_R = np.median(y)
        sigma_R = np.subtract(*np.percentile(y, [75, 25])) / 1.349

        # Expected number of deviations (95% confidence level):
#         n_dev = np.round(0.05 * n)
#         print(f"Expected number of data outside CI: {n_dev:.0f}")

        # Perform z-transform: sample quantiles z.i
        z_i = (y_os - mu_R) / sigma_R

        # Calculate cumulative probabilities p.i:
        i = np.array(range(n)) + 1
        p_i = (i - 0.5) / n

        # Calculate theoretical quantiles z.(i):
        z_th = norm.ppf(p_i, 0, 1)

        # Calculate SE or theoretical quantiles:
        SE_z_th = (1 / norm.pdf(z_th, 0, 1)) * np.sqrt((p_i * (1 - p_i)) / n)

        # Calculate 95% CI of diagonal line:
        CI_upper = z_th + 1.96 * SE_z_th
        CI_lower = z_th - 1.96 * SE_z_th

        # Make Q-Q plot:
        plt.plot(z_th, z_i, 'o', color='k', label='experimental data')
        plt.plot(z_th, z_th, '--', color='r', label='normal line')
        plt.plot(z_th, CI_upper, '--', color='b', label='95% CI')
        plt.plot(z_th, CI_lower, '--', color='b')
        plt.xlabel('Theoretical quantiles, $z_{(i)}$')
        plt.ylabel('Sample quantiles, $z_i$')
        plt.title(f"Q-Q plot - {column}")
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()


qq_plot(df_num.iloc[:,2:])

# Log transform and scaling using using pipeline
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer, MinMaxScaler

prep = Pipeline([('log1p', FunctionTransformer(np.log1p)),
                ('minmaxscaler', MinMaxScaler())]
               )
scaled_data = prep.fit_transform(df_num)

In [94]:
eigenvalues = pca.explained_variance_
eigenvectors = pca.components_
In [95]:
# Sort the eigenvalues and eigenvectors in descending order of the eigenvalues
order = eigenvalues.argsort()[::-1]
eigenvalues = eigenvalues[order]
eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, order]
In [96]:
# Calculate the proportion of variance explained by each eigenvector
total_variance = np.sum(eigenvalues)
variance_explained = eigenvalues / total_variance

# Calculate the cumulative proportion of variance explained
cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(variance_explained)

# Eigenvalues scree plot
plt.bar(range(1, len(eigenvalues)+1), variance_explained, align='center', color='skyblue')
plt.plot(range(1, len(eigenvalues)+1), cumulative_variance, '.-', color='navy')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of Variance Explained')
plt.title('Scree Plot')
plt.show()

PCA with legend¶

PCA, for example, identifies the linear combinations of the original features that explain the most variance in the data, allowing for the creation of a reduced set of features that still capture the important information. (ChatGPT)

from panel.interact import interact
from bokeh.plotting import figure
from bokeh.models import HoverTool, PrintfTickFormatter
import panel as pn
import numpy as np

# Distribution
def histogram(Plot_features, Treatment):
    
    '''this function will visualize distribution each plott per Treatment'''
    
    # Setting plot parameters
    df = df2[df2['Treatment'] == Treatment]
    
    # defining a plot
    p = figure(width=800, height=400, toolbar_location=None,
               title="Distribution of plott per Treatment:")
    p.xaxis.axis_label = "Distribution"
    p.yaxis.axis_label = "count"
    
    # setting the bins range
    start = min(df[Plot_features])
    end = max(df[Plot_features])
    bins = np.linspace(start, end, 20)
    
    # Plotting histogram
    hist, edges = np.histogram(df[Plot_features], density=True, bins=bins)
    p.quad(top=hist, bottom=0, left=edges[:-1], right=edges[1:],
           fill_color="navy", fill_alpha=0.8, line_color="white")
  
    # Adding hover tool
    hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[(Plot_features, "@top{0,0.00}")], mode="vline", formatters={Plot_features: 'printf'})
    p.add_tools(hover)
  
    return p

# Plotting interactive histogram
treatment = list(df2.Treatment.unique())
plot_param = list(dfn.columns)
histogram = pn.interact(histogram, Plot_features=plot_param, Treatment=treatment)

pn.Row(histogram)

from math import pi
from bokeh.palettes import Category10, Dark2
from bokeh.transform import cumsum

def doughnut_chart(Plott,Treatment):
    
    
    # Setting plot parameters
    df = df2[(df2['Treatment'] == Treatment) & (df2['plot'] == Plott)]
    gt = []
    
    grubbed_tubers = list(dfn_sorted.columns[2:6])
    for x in grubbed_tubers:
        gt.append(df[x].sum())
        
    data_dict = {}
    for key in grubbed_tubers:
        for value in gt:
            data_dict[key] = value
            gt.remove(value)
            break

    data = pd.Series(data_dict).reset_index(name='value').rename(columns={'index': 'grubbed_tubers'})
    data['angle'] = data['value'] / data['value'].sum() * 2 * pi
    data['color'] = Category10[len(data_dict)]

    p = figure(plot_height=400, plot_width=850, title="Doughnut chart for proportion of grubbed_tubers per plot per treatment",
               toolbar_location=None, tools='hover', tooltips='@grubbed_tubers: @value')

    p.annular_wedge(x=0, y=1, inner_radius=0.2, outer_radius=0.4,
                    start_angle=cumsum('angle', include_zero=True), end_angle=cumsum('angle'),
                    line_color="white", fill_color='color', legend='grubbed_tubers', source=data)

    return p

# Plotting interactive doughnut_chart for proportion of grubbed_tubers per treatment
treatment = list(df2.Treatment.unique())
plott = list(df2['plot'].unique())  # Use the unique values from the 'plott' column as dropdown options
doughnut_chart = pn.interact(doughnut_chart, Plott=plott,Treatment=treatment,)

# Displaying panel output
pn.extension()
pn.Row(doughnut_chart)

# pichart for grubbed_tubers
def pichart(Plott,Treatment):

    
    # Setting plot parameters
    df = df2[(df2['Treatment'] == Treatment) & (df2['plot'] == Plott)]
    gt =[]
    
        
    grubbed_tubers = list(dfn_sorted.columns[2:6])
    for x in grubbed_tubers:
        gt.append(df[x].sum())
            
    dict ={}
    for key in grubbed_tubers:
        for value in gt:
            dict[key]=value
            gt.remove(value)
            break


    data = pd.Series(dict).reset_index(name='value').rename(columns={'index': 'grubbed_tubers'})
    data['angle'] = data['value']/data['value'].sum() * 2*pi
    data['color'] = Dark2[len(dict)]
    

    
    p = figure(height=400,plot_width=850, title="Pie chart for proportion of grubbed_tubers per plot per treatment", toolbar_location=None,
               tools='hover',tooltips= '@grubbed_tubers:@value', x_range=(-0.5, 1.0))


    p.wedge(x=0, y=1, radius=0.3,
            start_angle=cumsum('angle', include_zero=True), end_angle=cumsum('angle'),
            line_color="white", fill_color='color', legend='grubbed_tubers', source=data)
    

    p.axis.axis_label = None
    p.axis.visible = False
    p.grid.grid_line_color = None

    return p

from math import pi
from bokeh.io import show
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, HoverTool
from bokeh.plotting import figure

def b_chart(Plott, Treatment):
    '''This function will visualize a horizontal bar chart for the proportion of sample_tubers per plot per treatment'''

    # Setting plot parameters
    df = df2[(df2['Treatment'] == Treatment) & (df2['plot'] == Plott)]
    sample_tubers = list(dfn_sorted.columns[22:28])
    gt = [df[x].sum() for x in sample_tubers]

    data_dict = {key: value for key, value in zip(sample_tubers, gt)}

    data = pd.Series(data_dict).reset_index(name='value').rename(columns={'index': 'sample_tubers'})

    p = figure(y_range=sample_tubers, plot_height=300, plot_width=850,
               title="Horizontal Bar Chart for Proportion of Sample Tubers per Plot per Treatment",
               toolbar_location=None, tools='hover', tooltips='@sample_tubers: @value')

    p.hbar(y='sample_tubers', right='value', height=0.8, source=data)

    # Add hover tooltip
    hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[('sample_tubers', '@sample_tubers'), ('Value', '@value')], mode='hline')
    p.add_tools(hover)

    return p

# Stacked plot for the tuber yield

def stackedbar(Plott):
    
    
     # setting parameter for ploting
    df= df2[df2['plot']== Plott]
    
    # geting a values for gender proportion
    treated =[]
    control =[]
    plot_features = list(dfn_sorted.columns[40:46])
    for x in plot_features:
        Treated = df[df['Treatment']== 'Treated']
        Control = df[df['Treatment']== 'control/common']
        treated.append(Treated[x].sum())
        control.append(Control[x].sum())
        
    data= {'plot_features':plot_features, 'Treated':treated, 'Control':control}
    Treatment =['Treated','Control'] 
    # setting parameters to plot
    p = figure(y_range= plot_features, height= 400, title='Proportion of Tuber Yield per Plot', 
    toolbar_location=None, tools="hover", tooltips="$name: @$name")

    p.hbar_stack(Treatment,y= 'plot_features',height=0.5, color=['blue','pink'], source= data, 
                 legend_label=['Treated', 'Control/Common'])
    p.xaxis.axis_label='tuber yield'
  

    p.y_range.range_padding = 0.1
    p.ygrid.grid_line_color = None
    p.legend.location = "bottom_right"
    p.axis.minor_tick_line_color = None
    p.outline_line_color = None
    
    return p

# visualizing the hbar plot for total number of death per gender per year

        Treated = df[df['Treatment']== 'Treated']
        Control = df[df['Treatment']== 'control/common']
        treated.append(Treated[x].sum())
        control.append(Control[x].sum())
        
    data= {'plot_features':plot_features, 'Treated':treated, 'Control':control}
    Treatment =['Treated','Control'] 
    # setting parameters to plot
    p = figure(y_range= plot_features, height= 400, title='Proportion of Tuber Yield (per hectare) per Plot', 
    toolbar_location=None, tools="hover", tooltips="$name: @$name")

    p.hbar_stack(Treatment,y= 'plot_features',height=0.5, color=['blue','pink'], source= data, 
                 legend_label=['Treated', 'Control/Common'])
    p.xaxis.axis_label='tuber yield per hectare'
  

    p.y_range.range_padding = 0.1
    p.ygrid.grid_line_color = None
    p.legend.location = "top_right"
    p.axis.minor_tick_line_color = None
    p.outline_line_color = None
    
    return p

# visualizing the hbar plot for total number of death per gender per year
years= list(df2['plot'].unique())
stackedbar =pn.interact(stackedbar, Plott= years)
pn.Row(stackedbar)
